'''Marcel Boll''' (15 September 1886, [[Paris]] – 12 August 1971, [[Paris]]) was a [[French people|French]] [[positivist]], [[education]]alist who played a prominent role in promoting the [[Vienna Circle]] in France.<ref name=PS>{{cite journal|last1=Schöttler|first1=Peter|title=From Comte to Carnap. Marcel Boll and the Introduction of the Vienna Circle|journal=Revue de Synthèse|date=25 April 2015|volume=136|doi=10.1007/s11873-014-0260-4}}</ref> He was professor of [[Chemistry]] and [[Electricity]] at [[HEC Paris]].
He translated works by [[Rudolph Carnap]], [[Phillip Frank]], [[Hans Reichenbach]], and [[Moritz Schlick]] into French.<ref name="GPS">{{cite book|last1=Stadler|first1=Friedrich|title=General Philosophy of Science: Focal Issues|date=2007|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9780080548548|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qUMuFaXjNjEC&pg=PA613&lpg=PA613&dq=Boll+Unified+Science+conference+Paris&source=bl&ots=KEI7gkOKo-&sig=yn9MyAgaa3bcbH8lQYc_1YfGm44&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwims-KJjNPXAhVBqxoKHWqZAAAQ6AEINjAB#v=onepage&q=Boll%20Unified%20Science%20conference%20Paris&f=false|accessdate=22 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>
